Introduction¶

This data set contains information about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb), including user ratings and revenue. We are going to investigate factors that may be attributed with higher revenue (adjusted for inflation) and genres that have been most popular with time.¶

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
In [22]:
def scacorr(a):
    print(a.describe())
    axes = pd.plotting.scatter_matrix(a, alpha=0.01,figsize=(16,16));
    corr = a.corr().as_matrix()
    for i, j in zip(*plt.np.triu_indices_from(axes, k=1)):
        axes[i, j].annotate("%.3f" %corr[i,j], (0.8, 0.8), xycoords='axes fraction', ha='center', va='center')

    return plt.show()

Conclusions¶

  • What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high revenues?
    • First, we considered movies with high revenue to be movies with revenu_adj greater than or equal 200M.we can find that movies with high revenues are movies with vote_average 6.3 Steven Spielberg is the director with greatest no. of movies with high revenues.We can see a positive correlation between revenue and budget here. Also, we can see directors with greatest no. of high revenue movies here. No of movies with high revenu have been increasing with years taking into account the inflation factor and we visualize so from the following figure. Descriptive statistics and histograms about features of high revenue can be found in th following link
  • Which genres are most popular from year to year?
    • This table demonstrates genres determined to be most popular annually from 1960 to 2015 according to popularity score.

Limitations¶

We can see that around 50% of dataset has budget and revenue value equal to zero. Although we have replaced these values with the mean value but this could have affected our results to some extent. Also we are having runtime values of zero. This could have a great effect on our correlations.
